In this article, Vice President Kamala Harris speaks about the importance of ending breast cancer and the personal significance it holds for her. She discusses her mother's work as a scientist and how her discoveries helped save women's lives. Harris mentions that significant progress has been made in the fight against cancer, with more people surviving and the death rate falling. She emphasizes that the new goals set by President Joe Biden to end cancer as we know it will transform, improve, and save lives. Harris shares her personal experience of losing her mother to cancer and highlights the need to continue working towards finding a cure. She introduces Dr. Edjah Nduom from Emory University School of Medicine as another leader in the field who has tirelessly worked to fight cancer. The article concludes at 2:02 P.M. EST.